<h2>Italian Pronunciation and Vocabulary</h2><p>Italian pronunciation is more consistent than English, with each letter having a predictable sound. This makes it easier for English speakers to read Italian aloud correctly once they learn the rules. Key sounds to master include the rolled R, the soft and hard C and G sounds, and the gn and gl combinations. FluentCards TTS provides accurate Italian pronunciation for every card. Listen to each word and repeat it aloud, focusing particularly on the double consonants which change meaning in Italian. For example, nono means ninth, while nonno means grandfather the double n makes the difference.</p><p>Italian vocabulary has many cognates with English because both languages have been influenced by Latin and French. Words ending in -tion in English often correspond to -zione in Italian, -sion becomes -sione, and -ty becomes -ta. Recognizing these patterns can dramatically accelerate your vocabulary acquisition. The Italian Basics deck in FluentCards includes 30 essential words to get you started, covering greetings, common verbs, numbers, and everyday vocabulary.</p>
